#Deploying Azure Virtual Machine Scale Set (VMSS) with Azure Load Balancer using Azure Portal

##Project Objective

Deploy a scalable web application using:
Azure Virtual Machine Scale Set (VMSS)
Azure Load Balancer
Virtual Network
Network Security Group
Autoscaling Rules

##Services Used
Microsoft Azure
Azure Virtual Machine Scale Sets
Azure Load Balancer
Azure Virtual Network
Azure Monitor

##Prerequisites
Azure Subscription
Contributor access
Basic knowledge of:
Networking
Virtual Machines
Load Balancer
Autoscaling

##Project Implementation – Step by Step

Step 1: Create Resource Group
Login to Azure Portal
Go to Resource Groups
Click Create
Name: VMSS-RG
Region: East US (or your preferred region)

Step 2: Create Virtual Machine Scale Set (VMSS)
Search Virtual Machine Scale Sets
Click Create
Choose:
Resource Group: VMSS-RG
Name: VMSS-Webserver
Image: Ubuntu 22.04 LTS
Size: Standard B2as v2
Instance count: 2
Authentication: SSH/Public key or Password

Step 3: Configure Load Balancer
Search Load Balancer
Click Create
Choose:
Resourse Group: VMSS-RG
Name: VMSS_LB
Frontend pool:Frontend01
Backend pool: Backens01 

Step 4: Configure Networking
During VMSS creation:
Create new Virtual Network
Subnet: default
Select Azure Load Balancer
Create new Load Balancer:
Type: Public
SKU: Standard
Add inbound rule:
Port 80 (HTTP)

Step 5: Install Web Server (Custom Script Extension)
After deployment:
Go to:
VMSS → Extensions → Add
Add Custom Script:
#!/bin/bash
#Install Apache web server
sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y apache2
#Start and enable Apache service
sudo systemctl start apache2
sudo systemctl enable apache2
#Get the server hostname
HOSTNAME=$(hostname)
#Create a sample webpage with the server name
sudo bash-c "echo\"<html><body><h1>Welcome to $HOSTNAME!</h1>
</body></html>\"> /var/www/html/index.html"

Step 6: Configure Autoscaling
Go to VMSS
Select Scaling
Enable autoscale
Configure:
Minimum: 2
Maximum: 5
Scale out: CPU > 70%
Scale in: CPU < 30%

Step 7: Test Load Balancer
Go to Load Balancer
Copy Public IP
Open in browser:
http://Public-IP

